    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-04-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="432"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d432">
                <head>432. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1" type="from">Rostow</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d432fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Country File, Pakistan, Vol. VII, Memos, 10/66–7/67.
                        Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-04-02">April 2, 1967</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Wheat and Oil Agreement for Pakistan</item>
                </list>
                <p>Here is the wheat agreement Gene Locke probably mentioned to you. He is paying
                    his farewell calls<note n="2" xml:id="d432fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_LEM1">Locke</persName> resigned his post as Ambassador
                        to Pakistan effective April 16. He was replaced by <persName
                            corresp="#p_OBHJ1">Benjamin H. Oehlert, Jr.</persName>, who was
                        appointed on July 27 and presented his credentials on August 16.</note> on
                    Pakistan’s senior economic ministers early tomorrow morning and would like to
                    give them an answer then. This would necessitate getting a cable out to him
                    early this evening. If that’s cutting it too close, we can get it to him
                    easily—if you approve—for his final call on Ayub Friday.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d432fn3">April 7.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Charlie Schultze’s memo (attached)<note n="4" xml:id="d432fn4">Dated April 3,
                        Schultze’s memorandum to the President dealt with the proposed <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">P.L.</gloss> 480 agreement with Pakistan.</note> lays
                    out the figures. In a nutshell, Pakistan has asked us for an added 250,000 tons
                    of wheat now to help break a rapid rise in prices stemming from drought
                    shortages. <persName corresp="#p_FOL1">Freeman</persName> and Hall propose
                    200,000—half to be charged against any <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1968 US
                    allocation for Pakistan.</p>
                <p>I recommend approval. Pakistan has done a sound job in agriculture. Approving
                    this program now would help Ayub with a tough economic-political problem. Even
                    doing this wouldn’t take us beyond average past levels (1.5 million tons) for
                    this year.<note n="5" xml:id="d432fn5">
                        <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>’s marginal handwritten
                        response reads: “OK, for either 200 or 250—I’d give him 250 but notify
                            <persName corresp="#p_LEM1">Locke</persName> at once.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
